<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4296546">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Fri, 01/03/2014 - 11:35 | <a href="/news/2014-01-03/sign-top-hedge-fund-hiring-junior-bitcoin-execution-trader#comment-4296546" class="active">4296546</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/thehound73" title="View user profile.">TheHound73</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/thehound73" title="View user profile."><img src="http://www.zerohedge.com/sites/default/files/pictures/picture-159269.png" alt="TheHound73&#039;s picture" title="TheHound73&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>Bitcoin does not require exponentially increasing amounts of energy. &nbsp;It does, however, require 100% more computational power than an (hypothetical) attacker. &nbsp;If that attacker is a superpower, then so be it.</p>
<p>Individuals around the globe are making their own independant decisions to use electricity and computational power to secure the bitcoin network. For that effort they are rewarded with BTC currency.</p>
<p>In contrast, how much energy is used for Bank and Visa Card servers, ATMs, armored trucks driving around, construction, lighting and heating of bank buildings, etc?</p>

